default&#xa0;
defaultTo achieve this 
defaultadvanced sorting systems us
defaulte a variety of
default analytica
defaultl methods 
defaultincluding
default near infrared, ultraviolet, x-ray, laser, polarized light, fluorescent light, electrostatic, melting point and other techniques. 
defaultThese methods are effective in keeping contamination of the main recycling streams with unwanted material low. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBiodegradable plastics should end up in biowaste bins. If such bins are not available they can still be clearly identified from their labels and sorted out for delivery to a biowaste processer. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, even
default in well working systems a
defaultn
default 
defaultintermingling
default of waste streams cannot be completely avoided.
default Non-biodegradable plastics can end up in the organic waste stream (e.g. misthrows) and biodegradable, compostable plastics might be found in 
defaultmechanical recycling (e.g. misidentification
default). It is already the case that conventional plastics find their way, in low volumes, to the wrong stream. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe can then say that in well run waste management facilities most r
defaultesidual bioplastic will end up as ‘mixed plastic’ until such a time as recovery is profitable. We can also say, even when incorrectly sorted, that b
defaultioplastics
default today
default 
defaultdo not enter the waste stream in sufficient volume to cause concern. Or at least no more concern than any other type of plastic. 
default&#xa0;
default3. The case against bioplastics is not evidence-baseddefault&#xa0;defaultVoices in some parts of the waste management industry claim that bioplastics are a serious disturbance to the established recycling streams of for example, PE or PET. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe following research and evidence refutes these assertions. It suggests the
default influence on the 
defaultcollection and processing of profitable 
defaultmaterials is 
defaultn
defaultegligible
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultBiobased Polyethylene (PE, not biodegradable or compostable)
default&#xa0;
defaultBiobased PE is obtained by polymerisation of ethylene monomers. Depending on the polymerisation process biobased LDPE or biobased HDPE can be produced. The only difference to fossil-based PE is the source, which is plant based (bioethanol made from sugar cane, sugar beet, wheat etc.). 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs a result fossil and plant based PE are chemically identical. They share the exact same physical properties.  Therefore biobased PE can be mechanically recycled with the fossil based PE in the corresponding recycling streams. 
defaultThere is no
default new
default issue.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultPLA/PBAT blends (compostable according to EN 13432)
default&#xa0;
defaultStudies
default by the University of Ha
defaultn
defaultnover [1]
default, [2]
default examined the
default influence of different compostable plastics on low-density polyethylene (LDPE).
default The tested mixtures contained between 0.5 % to 10 % foreign material. The LDPE contaminants were a PLA/PBAT
default blend, pure PBAT and a starch blend. They found:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe biodegradable polyester 
defaultPBAT 
defaultwas also tested as
default a
default possible contaminant for LDPE. The blending of 
defaultpure 
defaultPBAT with LDPE had no influence on the viscosity behaviour compared with pure LDPE and was affi
defaultr
defaultmed to have no influence on the processing properties. The values for melt flow rate were close to the ones of pure 
defaultL
defaultD
defaultPE and were also described to result in no distinctive disturbances during processing of the material.
default Optical changes could also not be observed.
default&#xa0;
defaultBelow 10% contamination there is no issue
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultStarch blends (compostable according to EN 13432)
default&#xa0;
defaultA study by BIOTEC 
default[3] 
defaulthas
default evaluated 
defaultt
defaultensile strength, elongation at break and specific impact resistance for mixtures of PE with possible contaminations
default with a starch/PBAT
default blend
default as
default well as 
defaultPP and P
defaultS. It was 
defaultshown that 
defaultthe biodegradable starch blend contaminates PE 
defaultno more than a contamination with conventional plastics
default as PS or PP. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn most case
defaults
default the properties of the mixtures 
defaultof PE 
defaultwith PS or PP as 
defaultcontaminants 
defaultshowed worse performances than 
defaultthe contamination of PE with a 
defaultstarch blend. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever
default, the same study found out that even lowest PET shares (2%)
default in a PE recycling stream
default 
defaultresults in serious problems. Due to the comparatively high melting temperature of PET (approx. 250°C), it was impossible to run a PE-based blown-film. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThese results suggest that 
defaultthe contaminating effect of a compostable plastic on PE is actually less than the contaminating effect of PET
default on PE. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA study by the University of Hannover [1] also examined a starch blend used in flexible packaging applications. It
default was found out that the influence on the viscosity and flow characteristics was only marginal up to the tested ratio of 10%. 
default&#xa0;
defaultConcerning the melt flow rate the influence on the processing properties was described as low considered with the pure LDPE. A change of colour was observed with 
defaultin
defaultcreasing amount of starch blend.
default&#xa0;
defaultTes
defaultts carried out at the Plastics T
defaultesting Laboratory Foundation of the Polytechnic Institute of Milan and the Proplast 
defaultL
defaultaboratories in Tortona/Italy
default (on behalf of CONAI, the National Packaging Consortium in Italy)
default 
default[4], 
defaulthave 
defaultconfirmed 
defaultthat it is possible to reprocess and recycle bags of a starch based materia
defaultl
default and traditional plastic shopping bag waste up to a concentration of 10%
default of starch-blends as input material
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCONAI
default 
defaultf
defaultound
default 
defaultthat flexible, compostable packaging can be recycled with common plastics packaging materials up to a content of 10% without any problems
default 
default[5]. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCONAI conclude
defaultd
default 
defaultthat 
defaulteven if 
defaultbiodegradable bags 
defaultare not disposed of
defaultf
default 
defaultproperl
defaulty they do not interfere with the recycling stream of conventional plastics.
